{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656807"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:18:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:18:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18767"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.17,0.02,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77419"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11499"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9880"},{"type":"tags","id":"11381"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77419"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood flow through vessels follows physical principles that determine how blood moves through the cardiovascular system. Several factors influence the rate of blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following changes would result in the greatest increase in blood flow through a vessel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Doubling the vessel radius","Doubling the pressure difference","Increasing vessel compliance","Halving the blood viscosity","Halving the vessel length"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood flow follows Ohm\u0027s law where Flow = Pressure/Resistance. \u003Cstrong\u003EDoubling the vessel radius\u003C/strong\u003E produces the largest increase in blood flow because radius has the most powerful effect on resistance. When radius doubles, resistance decreases by a factor of 16, resulting in a 16-fold increase in flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options would have less impact on blood flow:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoubling the pressure difference\u003C/strong\u003E only produces a two-fold increase in flow as pressure has a linear relationship with flow\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHalving the blood viscosity\u003C/strong\u003E only doubles the flow rate as viscosity has an inverse linear relationship\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHalving the vessel length\u003C/strong\u003E only doubles the flow rate as length has an inverse linear relationship\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing vessel compliance\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly affect steady-state flow\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis relationship explains why small changes in vessel radius through vasoconstriction or vasodilation have such profound effects on blood flow in the body.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood flow is directly proportional to the pressure difference and inversely proportional to resistance according to Ohm\u0027s law.","Vessel radius has the greatest impact on blood flow as it is raised to the fourth power in the flow equation.","Blood viscosity and vessel length are inversely proportional to flow rate."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T22:25:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T22:25:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11499"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77419"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10: